<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
	<key>CADisableMinimumFrameDurationOnPhone</key>
	<true/>
	<!--
		Export compliance. The app's only cryptography is standard,
		Apple-OS-provided: TLS via URLSession (Ktor Darwin) and SHA-256
		fingerprinting via CommonCrypto's CC_SHA256 for TOFU cert pinning.
		No SSH, VPN, bundled crypto libs, or proprietary algorithms. This
		qualifies for the Category 5 Part 2 exemption, so no export
		documentation upload is required at submission.
	-->
	<key>ITSAppUsesNonExemptEncryption</key>
	<false/>
	<!--
		ATS configuration for Lunamux's self-signed TLS endpoints.

		NSAllowsArbitraryLoads is required so that ATS does NOT reject the
		self-signed server cert before the URLSessionDelegate installed by
		:client's PinnedHttpClientFactory.ios gets a chance to inspect the
		server-trust challenge and either accept (capture/verify path) or
		cancel (pin mismatch). The delegate is the actual security check;
		ATS would otherwise pre-empt it with a generic chain failure.

		Do NOT add NSAllowsLocalNetworking back, however reasonable it looks
		next to the above. Per Apple, on iOS 10+ the presence of
		NSAllowsLocalNetworking (or NSAllowsArbitraryLoadsInWebContent /
		NSAllowsArbitraryLoadsForMedia) makes NSAllowsArbitraryLoads *ignored*,
		with an effective value of NO — silently re-enabling ATS. The keys read
		as additive but are not.

		That combination shipped here once and cost a real bug: LAN candidates
		kept working (local networking stayed exempt) while any fully-qualified
		public hostname — a Tailscale `*.ts.net` address — was rejected for
		presenting a non-CA-issued cert, before the pinning delegate ran.
		Android and Safari were unaffected, so it read as a VPN/routing fault.
		NSAllowsArbitraryLoads alone already covers local networking.

		See: https://developer.apple.com/documentation/bundleresources/information-property-list/nsapptransportsecurity/nsallowsarbitraryloads
	-->
	<key>NSAppTransportSecurity</key>
	<dict>
		<key>NSAllowsArbitraryLoads</key>
		<true/>
	</dict>
	<!--
		Local network access. Lunamux servers live on the same Wi-Fi as the
		phone, so reaching one is local-network access as far as iOS is
		concerned and the system alert is unavoidable. Without this string it
		appears with Apple's generic wording, which does not tell the user why
		a terminal app wants to scan their network. ConnectionHolder skips the
		identity lookups that would otherwise raise this alert during the
		built-in demo, so it fires on a real connect — where the LAN is
		genuinely needed and the ask makes sense in context.
	-->
	<key>NSLocalNetworkUsageDescription</key>
	<string>Lunamux connects to the Lunamux server running on your Mac over your local network.</string>
	<!--
		Camera access for QR device pairing (QRScannerSheet). iOS has no
		out-of-process code scanner like the Google code scanner Android uses,
		so the app drives AVCaptureSession itself and must carry this string.
		Pairing is the only feature that touches the camera; the app is fully
		usable without granting it (hosts can be added manually).
	-->
	<key>NSCameraUsageDescription</key>
	<string>Lunamux uses the camera to scan the pairing code shown by Lunamux on your Mac.</string>
	<!--
		Pairing deep link: lets the system Camera app (and anything else that
		opens a URL) hand a scanned lunamux://pair code straight to the app.
		The scheme must match PairingPayload.URI_PREFIX; LunamuxApp.onOpenURL
		is the receiving end. Mirrors the Android manifest's intent-filter.
	-->
	<key>CFBundleURLTypes</key>
	<array>
		<dict>
			<key>CFBundleURLName</key>
			<string>se.soderbjorn.lunamux.pair</string>
			<key>CFBundleTypeRole</key>
			<string>Viewer</string>
			<key>CFBundleURLSchemes</key>
			<array>
				<string>lunamux</string>
			</array>
		</dict>
	</array>
	<key>UIAppFonts</key>
	<array>
		<string>JetBrainsMono-Regular.ttf</string>
		<string>IosevkaTerm-Extended.ttf</string>
	</array>
</dict>
</plist>
